'''Michael William Morin''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|m|ɔr|ɪ|n}}; born May 3, 1991) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He has previously played in MLB for the [[Los Angeles Angels]], [[Kansas City Royals]], [[Seattle Mariners]], and [[Minnesota Twins]]. The Angels selected Morin in the 13th round of the [[2012 Major League Baseball Draft]], and he made his major league debut in 2014.

==Early life==
Morin was born in [[Andover, Minnesota]], and grew up in [[Leawood, Kansas]]. He is the son of Leatha Scalise Cline and Greg Morin. He was a four-year letterman at [[Shawnee Mission South High School]] in Kansas, and was drafted by the [[Kansas City Royals]] in the 40th round of the [[2009 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He did not sign, and instead attended the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].<ref name="heels">{{cite web|url=https://goheels.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=9288|title=Michael Morin Biography|date=2012|work=GoHeels.com|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref>

==College==
As a freshman at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], Morin made 24 appearances including one start. He recorded a 5-3 win–loss record with a 5.45 ERA, and had 3 saves. As a sophomore in 2011, Morin made 32 appearances including six starts. He became the Tar Heels closer, and recorded 10 saves. In 64 innings of work, he struck out 66 batters, and walked 18, while posting a 4.64 ERA.<ref name="heels"/>

While at North Carolina, Morin set the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]’s single-season saves record as a junior in 2012, with 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/mlb/kansas-city-royals/article2525901.html|title=Shawnee Mission South grad Mike Morin pitches an inning for Angels against his hometown team|work=kansascity|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://theacc.com/news/2012/6/7/51d0c349a0ee267cf05f78f7_131481020727032497.aspx?path=baseball Noting ACC Baseball: NCAA Super Regionals Edition - Atlantic Coast Conference | Official Athletics Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2012, he was named an [[All-American]] by ''[[Baseball America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goheels.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=3350&ATCLID=205499684|title=Baseball America Tabs Morin All-America|work=GoHeels.com|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref>

==Professional career==

===Los Angeles Angels===
The [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]] selected Morin in the 13th round, 417th overall pick, of the [[2012 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goheels.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=3350&ATCLID=205498441|title=Stallings, Morin Tabbed On Day Two Of MLB Draft|work=GoHeels.com|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> The following season he was an MiLB.com Angels Organization All Star and Angels Minor League Pitcher of the Year, as pitching for two minor league teams he was 3-3 with 23 saves and  a 1.93 ERA in 56 games, and struck out 76 batters in 70 innings.<ref>[http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?player_id=573046#/career/R/pitching/2019/ALL Mike Morin Stats, Highlights, Bio | MiLB.com Stats | The Official Site of Minor League Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.mlb.com/player/mike-morin-573046 Mike Morin Stats, Fantasy & News | MLB.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Morin was called up to the majors for the first time on April 27, 2014<ref>{{cite news|title=Angels bring up reliever, option Boesch to minors|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=10849595|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=April 28, 2014|date=April 27, 2014}}</ref> and made his debut three days later on April 30 against the [[Cleveland Indians]]. He earned his first career win on June 21 against Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://losangeles.angels.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=573046#gameType='R'&sectionType=career&statType=2&season=2015&level='MLB'|title=Mike Morin Stats, Video Highlights, Photos, Bio|work=Los Angeles Angels|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> Morin would remain in the Angels bullpen for the remainder of the season and posted a 4-4 record with a 2.90 ERA in 60 appearances (3rd among American League rookies).<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/morinmi01.shtml|title=Mike Morin Stats|date=2019|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1/> 

The following season, Morin took a step back following the success from a season prior, posting a 4-2 record with one save and an ERA of 6.37 in 47 games, with 41 strikeouts in 35.1 innings.<ref name="auto"/>  

In 2016, Morin matched his career high of 60 appearances from 2014 while going 2-2 and lowering his ERA to 4.37.<ref name="auto"/>  In 2017, Morin spent the majority of the season at the AAA level, pitching in 10 games for the Angels.<ref name="auto"/>  He was put on [[waivers (baseball)|waivers]] towards the end of the season.

===Kansas City Royals===

The [[Kansas City Royals]] claimed Morin off of [[waivers (baseball)|waivers]] on September 12, 2017. He spent the rest of the season in the majors, pitching in six games for the Royals, but was [[designated for assignment]] at season's end. 

===Seattle Mariners===
Morin was claimed off waivers by the [[Seattle Mariners]] on December 8, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Johns |first=Greg |url=https://www.mlb.com/mariners/news/mariners-sign-pitcher-mike-morin/c-263138740 |title=Mariners sign pitcher Mike Morin &#124; Seattle Mariners |publisher=Mlb.com |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=May 2, 2019}}</ref> He was designated for assignment before the 2018 season. Morin began the 2018 season with the [[Tacoma Rainiers]], and was promoted to the major leagues on June 8, pitching in three games for the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpug1170.com/news/007700-mariners-recall-daniel-vogelbach-and-select-mike-morin-from-aaa-tacoma/ |title=Mariners recall Daniel Vogelbach and select Mike Morin from AAA Tacoma &#124;1170 KPUG-AM |publisher=Kpug1170.com |date=December 8, 2017 |accessdate=May 2, 2019}}</ref>  He was designated for assignment on June 14, 2018. He was recalled on July 12, but then outrighted off the roster on July 20. He declared free agency on October 2, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2018/10/players-electing-free-agency.html|title=Players Electing Free Agency|work=MLB Trade Rumors|first=Jeff|last=Todd|date=October 8, 2018|accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref>

===Minnesota Twins===

On December 18, 2018, Morin signed a minor league deal with the [[Minnesota Twins]] that included an invitation to [[spring training]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2018/12/twins-to-sign-mike-morin.html|title=Twins To Sign Mike Morin|last=Todd|first=Jeff|work=mlbtraderumors.com|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018}}</ref> Morin began the 2019 season with the [[Rochester Red Wings]], and was promoted to the major leagues on May 2, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller |first=Phil |url=http://www.startribune.com/adalberto-mejia-on-injured-list-as-twins-recall-mike-morin-lineup-posted-at-target-field/509377522/ |title=Mejia on injured list; Twins promote Morin, start regulars against Astros |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=April 14, 2019 |accessdate=May 2, 2019}}</ref> In 23 games for the Twins in 2019 he was 0-0 with one save and a 3.18 ERA.<ref name="auto"/> 

===Philadelphia Phillies===

On July 20, 2019, the Minnesota Twins traded Morin to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in exchange for cash considerations.<ref>{{cite web|author=Erik Chambliss|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2019/07/20/phillies-acquire-right-handed-pitcher-mike-morin-in-trade-with-twins/|title=Phillies Acquire Right-Handed Pitcher Mike Morin In Trade With Twins|publisher=CBS Philly|date=July 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>

